.TH shield 7
.SH NAME
shield
\- build a shield.io badge from scratch
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
https://shields.io is a widely-used online resource for generating the
familiar small graphic
.B badges
seen on
.B GitHub
pages.
.PP
While it is pretty easy to find canned URLs to print nearly any badge
you need, learning how to construct the URL from scratch can be useful
if the canned output is not right for a given document.
.PP
This document introduces how to request a static badge.  
.SH THE URL
.PP
Here is an example of a URL that returns a badge icon:
.PP
.BI "https://img.shields.io/badge/" "lbl-msg-red" "?logo=gnu&logoColor=FFF"
.PP
Let's break it down to understand how the URL works:
.TP
.B Base
The
.B https\://img.shields.io/badge/
portion of the URL is the base. The text that follows dictates
the badge output.
.TP
.TP
.B Content
The
.I lbl-msg-red
is the
.B content
part of the URL.  It consists of one to three
parts that are separated by
.RB (\(lq - \(rq)
characters.
It consists of a mandatory
.BR label ,
followed by an
.B message
and
.BR color .
If the
.B content
has two parts, the second part must be the
.B color
or it will be ignored.
.IP
Spaces in either the label or message must be converted to
either an underscore
.RB \(lq _ \(rq
or
.RB \(lq %20 \(rq,
and doubled dashes or underscored are output as singles.
.IP
An optional
.RB \(lq .svg \(rq
can be added to the end of the
.B content
to help with content recognition.
.TP

.B Options
Additional options can follow the
.B content
part of the URL.
.B ?logo=gnu&logoColor=white
are
.I options
that decorate the badge.

